sg3
VGreat Headphones! Beware "Auto-Shutoff" Feature
p1150
sg5
VThe Good: Great Sound, Long Range, Wireless ChargeThe Bad: Auto Shut-off, A Little BulkyI have never reviewed anything before, but these headphones are definitely worth a few words. They have some great features and some unfortunate ones, but overall, they do exactly what they are designed to do, if you set them up right and understand how to use them properly.The base station is lightweight and sleek, and acts as a wireless charger for the actual headphones. This is a great feature, and really well designed. The two metal contact points on the headphones sit gently on the metal rest of the base station. Nothing plugs into the headphones, ever, and they never need batteries replaced. All you need to do to charge them is put them back where they go. A red light on the front of the base station lets you know that they're charging.The base station itself connects to a traditional power source via a small adaptor that, nevertheless, takes up two slots on a standard surge protector. If you have a lot of devices, you'll need to put it at the end ;) The audio runs via a male rca cable, from the base station to your audio source. That is extremely convenient, since it is the standard for most consumer audio products. With an rca to stereo mini adaptor, you can use these cans for pretty much anything.I purchased them as a gift for my grandmother, who is elderly and hard of hearing. I wanted her to be able to enjoy movies and television again without having to crank the volume or risk missing out on things. When I was there to set everything up for her, they worked like a charm.I have to admit, I was shocked myself at how clear the audio signal was. The bass is full and heavy, mids are solid, and the highs are crisp and clear. They work equally well for music, movies, and live television. They get LOUD. Louder than I expected. Loud enough for my grandmother. There is a frequency and volume control on the right side ear of the headphones, so you can make adjustments on the fly. On the left ear is a power switch. Simple, convenient, and user friendly.These are not Bluetooth. The base station broadcasts the signal from your audio device via radio transmission, directly to the receiver on the headphones. You can select a channel from a switch on the front of the base station. As long as the headphones are properly tuned into the broadcast from the base station, and within the very generous range (300ft), the sound is surprisingly good.  Get a snack, go to the bathroom, get the mail...you won't miss a beat. Keep the base station away from lights, power cables, and speakers, and there is very little interference at normal volume levels.I was able to use the output from my parents' television and set it up so that the headphones received an audio signal, even if the volume on the tv itself was turned all the way down. Eureka! Nana could watch a movie with the rest of the family or on her own without disturbing anyone else. I also thought they'd be great for watching tv while on the treadmill, but, alas, they're a little too bulky, and slip off soon after you start running.The biggest drawback of the Sennheiser RS120's is their Auto-Shut off feature. It is a confusing and frustrating experience if you are not well-informed about how it works. THIS IS IMPORTANT, and may be a deal breaker for a lot of people: if the headphones don't detect an audio signal after just a few minutes, they will stop sending a broadcast signal, and you will be greeted by a rush of loud static in both ears. It's an unpleasant surprise, but something that can be avoided altogether with minimal effort.After my mother called to complain that the headphones were no longer working, I took them home to see what was was happening. I hooked them up to my guitar amp to test them out. At first it was amazing. I could practice at night without waking my wife and son. I was able to play anywhere in the room, free from another tether to the amp! After a short break in playing, though, I lost contact with the base station and got the static full force.It was obnoxious and baffling to think that such a stupid feature would be included in something so well-designed in every other aspect. Why? WHY?? From what I've read in other reviews and online forums, it is for compliance with FCC broadcast regulations. Well, ok, then. Moving on...Other reviewers have offered up suggestions for dealing with the issue, and I want to make it clear that it has nothing to do with where it is plugged in or how it is powered. It is just designed this this way. One reviewer's suggestion for dealing with the problem was to crank the source audio, effectively tricking the base station into thinking it is receiving signal when nothing is actually playing. It works, but is not always practical for every situation, and it forces you to listen to the extra gain under your sound track.For me, the auto-shut off is not a deal breaker. Everything else works so well that I've learned to deal with it. A green light glows on the base station when you are broadcasting sound. When it is off, you'll get only static through the headphones. If you know this, you can proceed accordingly. When you pause your movie to go to the bathroom, you simply switch off the headphones before you lose the signal. When you come back, press play, and wait for the green light before switching them back on. After using them regularly, you'll do it automatically.It was the Auto-Shutoff that compelled me to write a review of this product to begin with. It makes them too complicated for my parents (let alone my grandmother) to use, unassisted. I get a lot of use out of them myself, and when we know that Nana is coming over, I'll bring them and set them up for her. In the meantime, I'm happy to finally be able to watch movies late at night when I get home from work. I'm thrilled to be able to play guitar at night without having to hunch in the corner like a troll.Unfortunately, now I owe my grandmother a new gift. She's so difficult to shop for.
